      {
         "id": "SECTION_introducttion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Introduction</h3>After using marks to count, new ideas were developed to improve this practice. This time, we created shapes (symbols) to represent our fingers. In this text, we explore counting ideas created by Indigenous people.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_drawing",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Basic shapes</h3>Let us remember one of the first counting methods represented in <b>Figure 1</b> (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a4f22e25-5839-407f-a1aa-634521d52b42'); return false;\">González Redondo, Francisco A., et al., <htdate0>, pp. 174 - 177, 180 - 182</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ceffba8a-43be-4de3-a5c8-27cdf81311b1'); return false;\">Puente, Francisco Barriga, <htdate1>, pp. 21 - 23</a>):</p><p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgBone\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgBone', '0%')\" src=\"images/Figura-9-Hueso-de-Lebombo.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Representation of baboon bone adorned with markings. This image, credited to Enrique Silván Pobes, is featured in the scholarly work of Francisco A. Gonzáles Redondo et al.<br />The original is available in ResearchNet (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('adaed4fb-9c50-4ef9-ab79-c65f3c0629b8'); return false;\">González Redondo, Francisco A., et al., <htdate2></a>), and its inclusion here is made possible by the authorization of Doctor Francisco A. Gonzales Redondo.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2010",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2020",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2010",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p>It is not common to have bones and tools available nearby, but we can create shapes (drawings) to represent our fingers. A shape that can help us achieve this goal is the rectangle:</p><p><div class=\"htTwoGeometricalRectangle\"> <div class=\"htFirstGeometrical\"><div class=\"htVerticalRectangle\"></div></div> <div class=\"htSecondGeometrical\"><div class=\"htHorizontalRectangle\"></div></div> </div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 2</b>: Demonstration of rectangles with different orientations: vertical (pink) and horizontal (blue).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p>Nature follows a rule: the large is made up of smaller parts. The rectangle, for example, can be made from another smaller shape, the square:</p><p><div class=\"htTwoGeometricalRectangle\"> <div class=\"htFirstGeometrical\"><div class=\"htHorizontalRectangle\"></div></div> <div class=\"htSecondGeometrical\"><div class=\"htSquare htColorSoftRed \"></div><div class=\"htSquare htColorSoftYellow\"></div></div> </div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 3</b>: Demonstration of a rectangle on the left, and on the right, the same rectangle made from squares of different colors.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Reducing...</b><br />We have used squares to make a rectangle. Can we also use even smaller squares to make other shapes?</div></div></center></p><p>Another closed shape, copied from nature, is the circle, which is present in our eyes:</p><p><div class=\"htTwoGeometricalRectangle\"> <div class=\"htFirstGeometrical\"><div class=\"htEye\"></div></div> <div class=\"htSecondGeometrical\"><div class=\"htCircle\"></div></div> </div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 4</b>: On the left, we have a representation of an eye. On the right, we have a circle. Eye inspired by the source code available on <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('35093614-5991-4b27-863a-5d2bf4d35905'); return false;\">CodePen</a>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Practice</h3></p><p class=\"lab\"><b>Practice</b><br />Draw the shapes learned in the space below and color the eye in <b>Figure 4</b> with the color you prefer:</p><p><table class=\"draw\"><tr><td>Circle</td><td>Square</td><td>Rectangle</td></tr><tr><td><img src=\"images/White.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img src=\"images/White.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td><td><img src=\"images/White.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\">Table 1: Space to draw the studied shapes.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_andes",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Our Fingers as Circles</h3>We explore the method <i>\"Yupana Inka Tawa Pukllay\"</i>, developed and published by Dhavit Prem of the Associação Yupank (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('2d2ea4a5-506b-4dbf-aaa4-3a10a8fbbd9c'); return false;\">Prem, Dhavit</a>) da Associação Yupanki (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8'); return false;\">Prem, Dhavit, <htdate0>, pp. 354 - 363</a>). This method follows the vertical model of Yupana as presented by Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1'); return false;\">Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman, <htdate1>, pp. 361 - 362</a>).</p><p>When we observe the <i>Yupana</i>, we can associate the circles represented on it with fingers. Using the arrows on the right side of the <i>Yupana</i>, see how our fingers are represented:</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2018",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1615",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Yupana</i></th><th>Left Hand</th><th>Right Hand</th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_center\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_bottom\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\"><span class=\"dot three_dot_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_up\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_center\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc3f1\"><span class=\"dot two_dot_bottom\"></span> <span class=\"dot two_dot_up\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"dot dot_center\"></span></td><td id=\"tc5f1\"><img onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg', '0%')\" id=\"leftHandImg\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Left_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc6f1\"><img id=\"rightHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Right_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc7f1\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></td></tr></table></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\">Table 2: Representation of a <i>Yupana</i> line according to Poma de Ayala (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8'); return false;\">Prem, Dhavit, <htdate0>, pp. 355</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1'); return false;\">Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman, <htdate1>, pp. 361 - 362</a>). CSS inspired by source code available on W3Schools (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('48dd9187-7ecc-4f54-a387-d9ecc2497de3'); return false;\">W3school</span></a>).</p><p>We do not show both hands with fingers raised because to represent them on the <i>Yupana</i>, more than one line with circles is necessary. We will present more details about this on another page.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2018",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1615",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_mesoamerica",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Couting with shapes</h3>The <i>Yupana</i> was not the only way Indigenous people used shapes to count. In another method, circles represent the fingertips, while rectangles represent all the fingers together (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('d1b7daa6-a743-4a66-9cfe-ff4286868f35'); return false;\">Hernández Mendoza, Aurelio & Pérez López, Felipa, <htdate0>, pp. 251</a> ). To represent all fingers down, they used an empty shell. Let us see how they represented our fingers:</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2013",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<table class=\"tawapukllay\" id=\"tblHandsCounting\"><tr><th>Left Hand</th><th>Right hand</th><th>Indigenous couting</th></tr> <tr id=\"tr0\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr1\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr2\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr3\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr4\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr5\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr6\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr7\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr8\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr9\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr10\"></tr>  </table>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\">Table 3: Representation of fingers counting with Indigenous methods. Source code available on the project's GitHub (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('240800f3-ede4-4deb-9d4e-915a3a03fa68'); return false;\">History Tracers Team, <htdate0>, Código-fonte</a>)</p><p>Basic shapes were not the only way used to represent fingers and counting among Indigenous peoples (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('ad11b3b2-8cdf-4d71-9cb7-2ac241850945'); return false;\">Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí, <htdate1>, pp. 31 (ResearchGate)</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('eca99877-c520-4569-a71c-0a5b3dd77dc4'); return false;\">Casares Contreras, Orlando & Cetina, José & Cabrera, Venus Sarahí, <htdate2>, pp. 31 (Revista)</a>), but for now, we will focus on these shapes.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2022",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2022",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Conclusion</h3>In this text, we explored some basic shapes used to represent our fingers and help us count without needing additional tools. These methods are efficient and easy to memorize, but they are not widely used everywhere. In the next text, we will present some symbols used for counting nowadays.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
